            p Congratulations on getting past the first cypher. Now we will move more into some basic tools used to hide and obfuscate data. MIME encoding (Base64), while not a cypher, is a common operation and one you should have in your toolkit of cypher cracking. Base64ing binary is a common way to transfer binary data that converts it to plain text, allowing for the easy transportation of large amounts of data. Virtually all email are sent with MIME encoding. There are Python libraries that do this conversion for you, but try it yourself so you understand what is really going on. MIME doesn't use direct ASCII codes to convert binary to a string, so you will need to use the key provided below in your encryption. To know that you have implemented correctly, try passing 'hello, world' into your function. If you get 'aGVsbG8sIHdvcmxk' as the output, you have completed the function.
            pre
              code.no-highlight
              | keyString = 'ABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZabcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz0123456789+/'
            p.solution click the box to reveal solution
            pre
              code.python
                | def MIMEencodeFromString(string):
                |   keyString = 'ABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZabcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz0123456789+/'
                |   # convert string into binary, excluding the 'b' inserted
                |   string = '0' + bin(int.from_bytes(string.encode(), 'big'))[2:]
                |   # add empty characters while necessary to fill out data
                |   while (len(string)) % 24:
                |     string +='00000000'
                |   # parse each six characters into base 10, and take correct character from the key
                |   return ''.join([keyString[int(string[i : i + 6],2)] for i in range(0, len(string), 6)])
            p Now that you have the encode function, the decode function shouldn't be too  complicated.
